1
00:00:00,859 --> 00:00:06,700
The triple exponential average (TRIX) is a
momentum indicator that shows the percentage

2
00:00:06,700 --> 00:00:10,820
change in a triple exponentially smoothed
moving average.

3
00:00:10,820 --> 00:00:17,050
This indicator it is designed to filter out
price movements that are considered insignificant

4
00:00:17,050 --> 00:00:18,370
or unimportant.

5
00:00:18,370 --> 00:00:23,400
TRIX is also implemented by traders to produce
signals that are similar in nature to the

6
00:00:23,400 --> 00:00:26,130
moving average convergence divergence (MACD).

7
00:00:26,130 --> 00:00:32,090
Although many consider TRIX to be very similar
to MACD, the primary difference between the

8
00:00:32,090 --> 00:00:37,690
two is that TRIX outputs are smoother due
to the triple smoothing of the exponential

9
00:00:37,690 --> 00:00:38,930
moving average (EMA).

10
00:00:38,930 --> 00:00:44,220
The TRIX indicator smooths price data and
then looks at the daily (or whatever time

11
00:00:44,220 --> 00:00:49,250
frame is being used) percentage movement of
that smoothed price data.

12
00:00:49,250 --> 00:00:54,410
This filters out much of the price noise that’s
seen on the price chart.

13
00:00:54,410 --> 00:01:00,140
TRIX will rise on sustained moves higher in
price, and will fall on sustained moves lower

14
00:01:00,140 --> 00:01:01,540
in price.

15
00:01:01,540 --> 00:01:06,960
Since TRIX is smoothed it takes time to react
to changes in price direction.

16
00:01:06,960 --> 00:01:12,290
This can be beneficial, because not every
little pullback means a trade should be exited

17
00:01:12,290 --> 00:01:15,850
or that the trend is going to reverse.

18
00:01:15,850 --> 00:01:21,250
How TRIX is calculated
It is a four step process to calculate TRIX.

19
00:01:21,250 --> 00:01:27,600
The indicator is “triple smoothed,” which
means we are taking a moving average of a

20
00:01:27,600 --> 00:01:30,350
moving average of a moving average.

21
00:01:30,350 --> 00:01:34,210
15-period exponential moving average (EMA)
using closing prices.

22
00:01:34,210 --> 00:01:40,240
15-period EMA of result from step 1.

23
00:01:40,240 --> 00:01:44,740
15-period EMA of result from step 2.

24
00:01:44,740 --> 00:01:47,810
1-period percent change of step 3.

25
00:01:47,810 --> 00:01:52,700
Step 4 is the TRIX, which will fluctuate from
period to period.

26
00:01:52,700 --> 00:01:57,420
A different number of periods could be used
in the calculation.

27
00:01:57,420 --> 00:02:02,620
Increasing the number of periods, for example
to 40, will decrease the sensitivity of the

28
00:02:02,620 --> 00:02:08,090
indicator and may be more useful to long-term
traders.

29
00:02:08,090 --> 00:02:13,121
Decreasing the number periods, for example
to 10, will increase the sensitivity of the

30
00:02:13,121 --> 00:02:18,340
indicator; if you are a short-term trader,
you may prefer this.

31
00:02:18,340 --> 00:02:26,239
Now, how to read the TRIX indicator
0.0 (zero level) on the indicator is used

32
00:02:26,239 --> 00:02:27,680
a baseline.

33
00:02:27,680 --> 00:02:33,739
When the TRIX is below 0.0, and especially
when it’s moving lower, the trend is considered

34
00:02:33,739 --> 00:02:35,660
down.

35
00:02:35,660 --> 00:02:41,010
When the TRIX is above 0.0, and especially
when it’s moving higher, the trend is considered

36
00:02:41,010 --> 00:02:42,950
up.

37
00:02:42,950 --> 00:02:49,810
TRIX helps confirm trends, indicates when
a trend reversal may be underway, and can

38
00:02:49,810 --> 00:02:53,489
also be used to generate trade signals.

39
00:02:53,489 --> 00:02:58,160
Divergences are another useful aspect of the
indicator.

40
00:02:58,160 --> 00:03:00,000
Bullish divergence is when the price makes
a lower low but the TRIX doesn’t.

41
00:03:00,000 --> 00:03:05,350
It indicates selling momentum is not as great
as it was on prior price drop.

42
00:03:05,350 --> 00:03:09,720
Weak selling momentum could lead to an eventual
reversal.

43
00:03:09,720 --> 00:03:14,680
Bearish divergence is when the price makes
a higher high, but the TRIX doesn’t.

44
00:03:14,680 --> 00:03:21,790
It signals weakening buying momentum, which
could result in an eventual reversal.

45
00:03:21,790 --> 00:03:27,320
As an additional step, a moving average (which
is visible) can be applied to the TRIX indicator.

46
00:03:27,320 --> 00:03:30,560
This is useful for providing crossover trade
signals.

47
00:03:30,560 --> 00:03:36,530
The moving average is typically of shorter
length than the number of periods used in

48
00:03:36,530 --> 00:03:38,090
the TRIX calculation.

49
00:03:38,090 --> 00:03:44,460
For example, if using a 20-period TRIX, a
7-period moving average could be applied to

50
00:03:44,460 --> 00:03:45,480
it.

51
00:03:45,480 --> 00:03:51,409
However, if you followed my channel, you already
know that I’m not a fan of moving average

52
00:03:51,409 --> 00:03:52,599
crossovers.

53
00:03:52,599 --> 00:03:58,420
If you want to back test some crossovers between
TRIX and another moving average, make sure

54
00:03:58,420 --> 00:04:03,660
you use it on higher timeframes, with small
positions.

55
00:04:03,660 --> 00:04:06,200
So how to trade using TRIX oscillator.

56
00:04:06,200 --> 00:04:13,440
A popular TRIX strategy is to watch for price
reversal signals, such a trend line or support

57
00:04:13,440 --> 00:04:18,909
or resistance breakout, which is confirmed
by a TRIX zero line crossover.

58
00:04:18,909 --> 00:04:27,110
For long trades, you buy when the TRIX crosses
above 0.0 if there is some evidence that the

59
00:04:27,110 --> 00:04:33,319
price has started to reverse higher (you need
to search for trend line breakout, higher

60
00:04:33,319 --> 00:04:36,319
swing high or higher swing low).

61
00:04:36,319 --> 00:04:44,469
For short trades, you go short when the TRIX
crosses below 0.0 if there is some evidence

62
00:04:44,469 --> 00:04:50,620
that the price has started to reverse lower
(so you need confirmation, namely a trend

63
00:04:50,620 --> 00:04:56,860
line or support or resistance breakout, lower
swing high or lower swing low).

64
00:04:56,860 --> 00:05:01,639
This strategy is simple and is mainly useful
for entries.

65
00:05:01,639 --> 00:05:07,169
Unfortunately, the entry point has little
regard for an appropriate place to put a stop

66
00:05:07,169 --> 00:05:08,240
loss.

67
00:05:08,240 --> 00:05:15,009
To control risk, a stop loss must be implemented,
preferably just above a recent high if taking

68
00:05:15,009 --> 00:05:21,729
a short position, or just below a recent low
if taking a long position.

69
00:05:21,729 --> 00:05:28,839
Waiting for the price to move back across
the zero line to exit the trade can mean giving

70
00:05:28,839 --> 00:05:30,689
back a lot of profit.

71
00:05:30,689 --> 00:05:39,460
For this reason, you shouldn’t rely in TRIX
indicator to offer an exit.

72
00:05:39,460 --> 00:06:11,610
Here are some examples of TRIX 0-crossover
signals, combined with price action breakouts.

73
00:06:11,610 --> 00:06:15,750
Divergence signals are another great way to
use the TRIX indicator.

74
00:06:15,750 --> 00:06:19,080
This is my favorite approach for this indicator.

75
00:06:19,080 --> 00:06:24,849
This occurs when the price action and indicator
are not aligned which is a precursor of a

76
00:06:24,849 --> 00:06:26,879
momentum shift.

77
00:06:26,879 --> 00:06:31,939
If you pay attention at this example, you
can see how the indicator puts in a retest

78
00:06:31,939 --> 00:06:35,719
of its lows, but the indicator on the second
test is above the zero line.

79
00:06:35,719 --> 00:06:41,089
This ultimately leads to a massive run higher,
where the indicator makes fresh new intraday

80
00:06:41,089 --> 00:06:44,860
highs on each push higher.

81
00:06:44,860 --> 00:06:51,119
In this example the second high had a lower
reading on the indicator, which is a precursor

82
00:06:51,119 --> 00:06:53,809
for a likely pullback.

83
00:06:53,809 --> 00:06:58,759
As always, try to incorporate price action
with this approach and don’t rely exclusively

84
00:06:58,759 --> 00:07:00,759
in the indicator.

85
00:07:00,759 --> 00:07:05,069
Price action first, confirmed by the indicator.

86
00:07:05,069 --> 00:07:10,119
Now, bearish divergences do not work well
in strong uptrends.

87
00:07:10,119 --> 00:07:16,800
Even though momentum seems to be weakening
because the indicator is producing lower highs,

88
00:07:16,800 --> 00:07:23,759
momentum still has a bullish bias as long
as the indicator is above its centerline.

89
00:07:23,759 --> 00:07:30,169
Upward momentum may be less positive, but
it is still positive as long as it stays above

90
00:07:30,169 --> 00:07:31,849
0 baseline.

91
00:07:31,849 --> 00:07:35,639
The rise is just not as fast as before.

92
00:07:35,639 --> 00:07:38,719
The opposite is true for bullish divergences.

93
00:07:38,719 --> 00:07:42,099
These do not work well in strong downtrends.

94
00:07:42,099 --> 00:07:47,989
Even though the indicator shows less downside
momentum with higher lows, downward momentum

95
00:07:47,989 --> 00:07:54,330
is still stronger than upward momentum as
long as the indicator remains below its centerline.

96
00:07:54,330 --> 00:08:00,050
So, the trick is separating the bad signals
from the good signals.

97
00:08:00,050 --> 00:08:05,270
Which means you must read price action and
identify the appropriate support and resistance

98
00:08:05,270 --> 00:08:09,659
levels and patterns.

99
00:08:09,659 --> 00:08:34,620
Here are some examples of valid TRIX divergences.

100
00:08:34,620 --> 00:08:37,589
So what are the advantages of TRIX.

101
00:08:37,589 --> 00:08:43,579
Two main advantages of TRIX over other trend-following
indicators are its excellent filtration of

102
00:08:43,579 --> 00:08:49,630
market noise and its tendency to be a leading
than lagging indicator.

103
00:08:49,630 --> 00:08:55,079
It filters out market noise using the triple
exponential average calculation, thus eliminating

104
00:08:55,079 --> 00:09:00,740
minor short-term cycles that indicate a change
in market direction.

105
00:09:00,740 --> 00:09:05,930
It has the ability to lead a market because
it measures the difference between each bar's

106
00:09:05,930 --> 00:09:09,720
"smoothed" version of the price information.

107
00:09:09,720 --> 00:09:15,750
When interpreted as a leading indicator, TRIX
is best used in conjunction with other market-timing

108
00:09:15,750 --> 00:09:21,300
indicator - this minimizes false signals.

109
00:09:21,300 --> 00:09:27,500
Regarding TRIX limitations, the TRIX doesn’t
always reflect what is happening in the price.

110
00:09:27,500 --> 00:09:31,980
The price may be trending higher while TRIX
is trending lower.

111
00:09:31,980 --> 00:09:37,660
We talked before about divergences which signals
a potential end to the trend, but a trend

112
00:09:37,660 --> 00:09:42,790
can persist for a very long time even on weakening
momentum.

113
00:09:42,790 --> 00:09:49,089
Using the TRIX in this situation can be deceiving,
and can result in missing out on some great

114
00:09:49,089 --> 00:09:51,170
upside potential in the price.

115
00:09:51,170 --> 00:09:57,490
That’s why, when used alone, TRIX can offer
false signals.

116
00:09:57,490 --> 00:10:00,589
False crossovers are another common issue.

117
00:10:00,589 --> 00:10:06,589
A false crossover is when the TRIX crosses
above or below the zero line, only to snap

118
00:10:06,589 --> 00:10:11,269
back the other way, resulting in a losing
trade.

119
00:10:11,269 --> 00:10:15,290
False signals can result in many losses within
a short period of time.

120
00:10:15,290 --> 00:10:20,970
That’s why I recommend to use longer-term
trend analysis to help avoid some of these

121
00:10:20,970 --> 00:10:22,620
false signals.

122
00:10:22,620 --> 00:10:30,610
Ideally, only take buy signals when an overall
uptrend is underway, and sell signals when

123
00:10:30,610 --> 00:10:33,820
an overall downtrend is underway.

124
00:10:33,820 --> 00:10:37,720
The indicator also has no regard for setting
a stop loss.

125
00:10:37,720 --> 00:10:44,589
A stop loss must be placed manually above
a recent high (shorts) or below a recent low

126
00:10:44,589 --> 00:10:46,899
(longs).

127
00:10:46,899 --> 00:10:52,050
If there is no respective high or low near
the entry point, maybe you should consider

128
00:10:52,050 --> 00:10:55,279
avoiding the trade.

